🔷 Summary & Recommendation
Summary
You explored three viable governance models for applying masking policies in a multi‑account Snowflake setup:

Manual Steward Attachments  
Data Stewards explicitly attach masking policies after Data Engineers deploy tables.

Tag‑Driven Masking (Stewards apply tags)  
Data Stewards apply tags, and policies auto‑apply based on those tags.

Metadata‑Driven Governance (Stewards own metadata; pipeline applies tags/policies)  
Data Stewards maintain a YAML/table describing which columns require governance.
The pipeline merges DDL (engineers) + metadata (stewards) and applies tags/policies.

All three work, but they differ in automation, safety, and operational overhead.

⭐ Recommendation
The Metadata‑Driven Governance Model is the strongest and most scalable:
It preserves strict separation of duties
It prevents Data Engineers from unmasking data
It avoids CREATE OR REPLACE wiping out policies
It enables automated drift detection
It centralizes governance logic in steward‑owned metadata
It allows pipelines to enforce governance consistently and automatically

This is the model most large enterprises eventually adopt.

🔷 Detailed Reference: The Three Approaches
Below is a clean, structured breakdown of each model — what it is, how it works, pros, cons, and when to use it.

1. Manual Steward Attachments (Baseline Model)
How it works
Data Engineers deploy tables/views.

Data Stewards run ALTER statements to attach masking policies.

Two separate pipelines:

Engineering pipeline → DDL

Steward pipeline → governance ALTERs

Pros
Strong separation of duties

Very explicit governance actions

Easy to audit

No risk of engineers unmasking data

Cons
Requires two pipelines

CREATE OR REPLACE wipes out policies until steward pipeline reattaches them

Slower workflow

More manual coordination

Best for
Teams early in governance maturity or with strict manual approval processes.

2. Tag‑Driven Masking (Stewards apply tags)
How it works
DG team binds masking policies to tags.

Data Stewards apply tags to columns.

Masking policies auto‑apply based on tag.

Pros
Highly automated

No need for separate ALTER statements

Very clean CI/CD

Easy to scale across domains

Cons
Only safe if Data Engineers cannot apply/unset tags

Requires strict privilege control

CREATE OR REPLACE still wipes tags unless pipeline re‑applies them

Harder to validate drift without metadata

Best for
Teams with strong privilege discipline and a desire for automation.

3. Metadata‑Driven Governance (Recommended Model)
How it works
Data Engineers own DDL repo.

Data Stewards own governance metadata (YAML or Snowflake table).

Pipeline merges both sources of truth:

Deploys DDL

Applies tags/policies based on steward metadata

Pipeline validates that all required columns are tagged/masked.

Pros
Strongest separation of duties

Fully automatable

CREATE OR REPLACE cannot break governance (pipeline re‑applies tags/policies)

Drift detection is built‑in

Governance metadata is version‑controlled

Pipeline is the only entity with combined privileges

Scales beautifully across many domains

Cons
Requires a more sophisticated pipeline

Requires metadata modeling

Requires careful privilege design

Best for
Enterprises with multiple domains, strong governance requirements, and CI/CD maturity.

🔷 Why the Metadata‑Driven Model Wins
It solves every major problem:

1. CREATE OR REPLACE wiping out policies
Pipeline re‑applies tags/policies automatically.

2. Engineers accidentally unmasking data
Engineers cannot apply/unset tags or policies.

3. Stewards needing to manually run ALTER statements
Pipeline handles it automatically.

4. Drift between code and actual masking
Pipeline validates against steward metadata.

5. Governance consistency across domains
All domains follow the same contract.

6. Clear separation of duties
Engineers define structure

Stewards define governance

Pipeline enforces both

This is the model that keeps governance strong and keeps engineering velocity high.

